The '''Eurovision Song Contest 1958''' was the third [[Eurovision Song Contest]] and was held on 12 March 1958 in [[Hilversum]]. The convention  that the winning country from a year hosted the following year's contest was introduced in this year. France's win was their first. It was the last time to date that the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest|United Kingdom]] did not enter the contest. Unlike the competition in 1956, 1957 limited one song per country, they were still limited to entering a single song in 1958, which has remained the policy to date. Together with 1956, it is the only contest that has not featured a single song in the English language.<ref name=ESC1958>{{cite web|title=Eurovision History <U+2013> Hilversum 1958|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=275#Participants|work=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> 

== Location ==
{{location map+|Netherlands
| width   = 250
| float   = left
| caption = Location of the host city in the [[Netherlands]].
| places  =
{{location map~|Netherlands|lat=52.23|long=5.18|label=[[Hilversum]]|position=right}}
}}

{{Details|Hilversum|the host city}}
Hilversum is a municipality and a town in the [[Netherlands]], in the province of [[North Holland]]. Located in the region called "[['t Gooi]]", it is the largest town in that area. It is surrounded by [[heathland]], [[forest|wood]]s, [[meadow]]s, lakes, and smaller villages. Hilversum is part of the [[Randstad]], one of the largest [[conurbation]]s in Europe.

== Format ==
The juries were not in the studio as in 1956. As in 1957, this year they stayed in their own countries, listening to the event. Once the songs had all been sung, juries sent their results via telephone. The Italian entry was not picked up properly in some of the other countries, which meant that after all the other songs had been presented, [[Domenico Modugno]] had to sing it again. Later on, it became very successful in the United States, where it has become commonly known as [[Volare (song)|Volare]], and got two [[Grammy Awards of 1959|Grammy Awards]]. It is one of few Eurovision songs that has reached No. 1 in the US singles charts. At the 50th anniversary show "[[Congratulations (Eurovision)|Congratulations]]" in 2005, it was elected the 2nd best Eurovision entry ever.

The interval acts was music by the [[Metropole Orkest]], under the lead of conductor Dolf van der Linden. This year, there were two interval acts; one in the middle, one after all the songs were played.  It was also the only year that the host country came last place, and the first time more than one country came last.

== Participating countries ==
{{Further|List of countries in the Eurovision Song Contest}}
[[Sweden in the Eurovision Song Contest|Sweden]], a country that would later be one of the most successful in the contest, debuted this year. While the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest|United Kingdom]] decided to withdraw from the contest.

After the contest, the Italian entry ''"Nel Blu Dipinto Di Blu"'' (more commonly known as ''"Volare"'') by Domenico Modugno went on to becoming a worldwide hit and to date, it is one of the most successful Eurovision songs in the history of the Contest. The entry managed to reach the No.1 spot in the [[Billboard (magazine)|US-American Billboard Charts]] and was also awarded three [[Grammy Award|Grammies]].<ref name=ESC1958/>

=== Returning artists ===
The contest saw the return of four artists who had participated in previous editions of the contest. Fud Leclerc for Belgium (previous entry in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1956|1956]]); Margot Hielscher for Germany (previous entry in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1957|1957]]); Corry Brokken for Netherlands (previous entry in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1956|1956]], and also the winner from the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1957|1957 contest]]); and Lys Assia for Switzerland (winner of the first contest in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1956|1956]], and also participated in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1957|1957]]).
